title: For Sale/Trade:  FN Hi Power
postcontent:
So I bought this a long time back. Haven't shot it much. Tried to trade it off one time before now but withdrew the trade offer before it had a chance to take off because I thought I might be making a mistake. At this point, it's either I trade it for a gun I want and like to shoot, or I start doing drastic things to the gun which will wreck what collectable value is left in it.

Now to start off with, I have an email from FN stating that the serial number this gun used was made in 1946, others have said 44-45, but I believe that FN is dead on with 1946. Having said that, I can attest that the slide portion was an arsenal replacement because as you can see it has an external extractor, which didn't come along until later. As I understand it the A proceeding the serial number on the frame is something that makes it a little more collectable. All the markings match up properly and I am including links to those pictures.

Right now it has (1) split-tongue base mag serial number matching to the gun (these are extremely rare and denote the 1944-195x time frame), two OEM 13rd Browning Mags, two 15rd MecGar Mags, an Israeli 1911 (Like the Blackhawk Serpa) holster modified to fit the 1911, a Hunter leather holster, Original WWII well-worn walnut grips, Craig Spegel style grips (cocobolo).

title: For Sale:  Enfield 303 British 8/49 #4 Mk II, No. 4 Mk 2 Number 4 Mark II
postcontent: 8/1949 “F” series Numbers Matching. 42 more photos located here: ( http://s1061.photobucket.com/albums/t462/DeltaCompany/303%20Enfield%20No%204%20Mk%20II/ ) Manufactured by Fazakerley ( F ) - the finish is original, a type of baked on paint system that was invented by the British - other times known as Suncorite. According to website, the No4 Mk II (or Mk2) was adopted in 1949, with production at ROF-Fazakerley in July, 1949 until 1955. Fazakerley was the only plant to manufacture the No4 Mk2  .A first year production MK2 to be exact and one of the first few months off the line!  A fairly rare specimen and one to be proud of. The biggest difference in the MK2 and the MK1 is that the trigger of the MK2 is pinned to the receiver instead of the trigger guard. Pinning the the trigger to the receiver made it a more consistent in that the relationship of the trigger to the sear never changed save for wear.  I bought it over 20 years ago when it was still arsenal wrapped in cosmoline to include complete barrel end to end encased in cosmoline.  I was young and stupid (weren’t we all) and made the decision to “Sporterize” the original stock with the intended use for Deer and Elk hunting. The original stock is pictured below with wood in fantastic condition.  I recently purchased for $120 an arsenal NEW – NEVER FINAL FITTED/MOUNTED Dark Hardwood Stock that is simply fantastic.  Normal pressure marks on buttstock, one slight chip near triggerguard.  Note you will need to remove/have removed about 3/8” of wood  from the inside front of the action inletting to get the action to fit as this was never arsenal mounted as I am told…however this means you will have a custom fit stock to the dimensions of your action for impeccable service. I have pictured on:  Finish on Metal is incredible for its age and as compared to other similar rifles being sold on GunBroker.  Magazine, Action, Bolt numbers match. Bore is brilliant bright metal with DEEP rifling. Mounted on the action is a “B-Square” scope mount that uses the existing features of the action to attach…NO DRILLING of the action has taken place. Scope is a BSA (wanted to stay with British Theme) classic series 3-12x50mm with metal screw-in protectors for the glass.  I have the original screw that fits in the side of the action as well as the Original Micrometer iron sights with the cross-pin, pressure springs, etc. required to put back to original.  I will as well include the following accessories:  Blade Bayonet dated 52? That has never been out of the original factory cosmoline/encasing with original arsenal wax paper. Sling Swivel and Barrel Clamp, barrel band, and extra Brass Buttplate that has never been mounted…I cleaned off the original arsenal cosmoline so you could see the perfection of the buttplate.  Guys, lets’ be honest – everything is here to put back to original specification, and you will be very hard pressed to find such a fine example of a #4 Mk II anywhere for under $600. I require a bill of sale to be signed by the purchaser. Please call me with questions REDACTED

 Additional information about the Ruger LCP 380: http://www.ruger.com/products/lcp/index.html 
Weighing just 9.4 oz (266.5 g) this is Ruger's first entry into the field of tiny, ultra-light defensive pistols.[4] LCP stands for "Lightweight Compact Pistol" and was designed in direct response to customer requests for a compact firearm for use by police as a back-up, and as a defensive handgun for civilian concealed carry needs.[5]
 The pistol has a glass-filled nylon frame, a two-finger grip, and a through-hardened blued steel slide. It is similar in appearance to the Kel-Tec P-3AT which weighs 8.3 oz. and uses a similar tension spring for the lightweight hammer, identical locked breech mechanism, and similar takedown method. The main differences are the Glock style extractor and the incorporation of an external slide stop. It is possible to tell if there is a round chambered by looking at the "view hole" next to the extractor
 Additional information about the Laserlyte laser: http://www.laserlyte.com/products/ck-amf
 LaserLyte answers the growing demand for lasers specific to the increasingly popular conceal carry market with the new Ruger LCP Side Mount Laser (CK-AMF). At half the cost of a leading competitor, the CK-AMF fits on the side of the Ruger LCP and the Kel-Tec .380 and .32. Easy to mount on the gun by simply pushing out and replacing the stock pins with the new screws (included). Then push the ergonomic activation button with the index finger and the laser is on target. The CK-AMF design works also as a finger guide that allows for safe trigger control without blocking the laser beam. The programmable laser features a pulse or constant on mode and also has an auto-off function to prevent an unwanted battery drain. The side mounted laser allows the pistol to fit in virtually any nylon pocket holster. The new LaserLyte Ruger LCP Side Mount Laser is compact and light, and foremost – deadly.

Thanks for looking and if you’re interested, please email me.
 Dave
